# gitlab-mr CLI (shell skill)

Thin JSON-first wrapper around GitLab REST **`/merge_requests` + `/discussions`** for agents and scripts. Prefer Cursor **GitLab MCP** when the repo already exposes it; use this CLI when you only have a shell and **`GITLAB_TOKEN`**.

## Install and PATH

From the **checked-out** `gitlab_plugin` repo root (use your real path, e.g. `~/misc/gitlab_plugin`, not another machine’s `$HOME`):

```bash
python3 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -e .
```

Until you add the venv **`bin`** to `PATH`, **`gitlab-mr: command not found`** is expected—in that case invoke **`.venv/bin/gitlab-mr`** from the repo root, or install with **pipx** so `gitlab-mr` lands on `PATH`.

On PEP 668–managed system Python, always install inside a venv.

## Environment

| Variable | Purpose |
|----------|---------|
| **`GITLAB_TOKEN`** | Personal access token. This CLI reads **only** this name (not `GITLAB_PRIVATE_TOKEN` unless you `export GITLAB_TOKEN=…` yourself). Scopes: at least **`read_api`** for `discussions`; **`api`** for `reply` and `create`. |
| **`GITLAB_URL`** | Base URL for self-managed GitLab. Omit on **gitlab.com**. Wrong host ⇒ `401`/wrong project. |

Requests use GitLab’s **`PRIVATE-TOKEN`** HTTP header—if **`curl`** with `$GITLAB_TOKEN` returns **200** but **`gitlab-mr`** returns **401**, upgrade/reinstall so you have the current client version; old builds sent the wrong header name.

Never print tokens in transcripts or commits.

## Help and version

Every command accepts **`--help`** and **`-h`**. Root **`--version` / `-V`** prints the package version.

Examples:

```text
gitlab-mr -h
gitlab-mr discussions -h
gitlab-mr create --help
gitlab-mr -V
```

## Typical workflow

1. **`discussions`** (alias **`review-comments`**) — list threaded review payloads:

   ```text
   gitlab-mr discussions "https://gitlab.com/ns/repo/-/merge_requests/12"
   gitlab-mr discussions 12 -p ns/repo
   ```

2. **`discussion_id`** — take from JSON; each thread has `notes[]` with bodies and authors.

3. **`reply`** — post inside that thread (`--discussion-id`, body via **`--body`**, **`--body-file`**, or stdin).

4. **`create`** — open an MR (**`--source-branch`**, **`--target-branch`**, **`--title`**, plus description via **`--description`**, **`--description-file`**, or piped stdin).

**`--dry-run`** on `discussions` / `reply` / `create` prints resolved routing **without HTTP** (token presence only as a boolean hint; GitLab is not contacted).

## When to prefer MCP instead

Repos with **`gitlab_mr_*`** MCP tools cover broader ALM flows (pipelines, search, approvals orchestration). This Skill is for **minimal shell automation** or environments without MCP.

